**Content Approach:** Most competitors publish design galleries — 10–30 images with thin descriptive captions. They name designs ("glazed sage mani", "gingham nails") but rarely explain *why* a design works, when to wear it, or how to choose between variations. Visual-first, context-light.

**Visual Patterns:** Competitors average 10–20 images; inspirational-intent content on this topic performs better with rich image volume. Top performers (Real Simple, InStyle, Who What Wear) use inline photography with attribution.

**Recommended Image Count:** 10–12 images. Inspirational intent needs strong visual proof. Spring/summer peak means audiences are actively looking for looks to screenshot and show their nail tech.

### Competitor Gaps

**Unanswered Questions Competitors Are NOT Answering**
- How does sage green actually look different across skin tones — not just "it suits all skin tones" (generic) but which shade of sage for which undertone
- What makes sage green different from pistachio, mint, olive — where exactly does one shade end and another begin
- Can you wear sage year-round and specifically what does a fall/winter sage look look like vs spring sage
- Which finish (matte, glossy, velvet, chrome) changes the *vibe* of sage the most
- What nail shape makes sage green look its best on short nails specifically
- How to style sage nails with outfits — beyond "it goes with everything"
- Why sage green replaced butter yellow as spring 2026's hero neutral (the cultural context)
- What the "dark sage" or olive end of the spectrum offers vs soft pastel sage — when to choose each

**Missing Semantic Territory**
- Seasonal shift narrative: sage as the answer to butter yellow fatigue
- Wabi-sabi / organic design influence driving the 2026 earth-tone nail moment
- Bridesmaid dress colour crossover (sage is 2026's top bridesmaid shade — nails to match)
- Pistachio distinction: where pistachio ends and sage begins
- The "Garden Glam" framing — sophisticated enough for events, grounded enough for daily wear
- Finish-as-colour: how velvet matte vs high gloss creates what feels like two completely different shades

**Audience Blind Spots**
- No one is answering "which brand of sage green nail polish actually photographs the way it looks on Instagram"
- No one is writing for the reader who has seen sage everywhere and wants to understand what makes it *the* spring 2026 shade before committing
- Very little genuine guidance on the dark sage / olive end of the spectrum for those who want edge without drama
- No seasonal styling pairings — sage green with what outfit, accessories, and occasion

### Our Strategic Approach

**Differentiation:** We win not by showing more designs than competitors, but by giving readers the *context* to choose their design — what shade, what finish, what shape, what season, what skin tone. Every section answers a real question competitors ignore.

**Structure Plan:** Lead with the cultural moment (why sage now), move through the shade spectrum (pistachio → soft sage → dark sage), then spring and summer looks, then year-round styling, with skin tone and finish guidance woven throughout.

**Tone Direction:** Warm expert with editorial confidence — the voice of someone who genuinely loves this colour and knows why it works.

